Homicide detectives are exposed to a lot of disturbing and upsetting things in the course of their jobs, including violence, death, and the devastation caused by these events. They see the victims, the families, and the perpetrators, and they know that they cannot change what has happened. Many of them deal with this stress by working even harder to find justice for the victims and their families. Others turn to alcohol or other substances to numb the pain and avoid facing the reality of their situations. Still others seek counseling or therapy to help them process what they have seen and experienced.

Ultimately, there is no one way to stay sane after witnessing traumatic events. Everyone processes things differently, and what works for one person may not work for another.
output_2: Homicide detectives, like all police officers, must undergo extensive training and counseling to help them cope with the disturbing scenes they may encounter.  Most detectives develop a certain emotional distance from the crime scenes they investigate, which helps them stay professional and focused on the task at hand.  They also rely on their colleagues and support networks of family and friends for support.  Overall, homicide detectives are a resilient and tough group of professionals who are well equipped to deal with the psychological challenges of their job.

instruction: Write a short story based on the following prompt:  You find an abandoned puppy hiding from the rain on your doorstep. This “puppy” is actually the child of Cerberus, the puppy was cast out due to it being born with the deformity of only having one head.
output_1:
She was cold, scared, and alone. The rain seemed to wash away any trace of her scent. She didn't know where to go, or what to do. All she knew was that the voices in her head were calling her home. It was her mother's voice, and she was the only thing she had left. The world was too loud and bright, it hurt her head to think. So she closed her eyes, and waited.
She felt the air grow warmer, smelled a scent she knew all too well. Her mother was coming, and she was taking her home. The voices in her head were loud, she could hear them all at once. They were screaming, yelling, begging her to come back. She didn't want to be home, but she couldn't disobey her mother. She opened her eyes, and watched her mother as she dragged her away. She struggled, but she knew it was no use.
Her mother threw her into a hole, and left her there. She was alone, but not for long. The voices were everywhere. She could hear them in the wind, the rain, and the earth. She tried to scream, but no sound came out. Her mother had taken her voice. Her mother was angry, but she knew why. Her mother was coming back, and she had to be ready.
So she waited, and listened.
output_2: It had been raining all day, and the streets were empty as I made my way to the market. The sky had opened up, dumping more rain than the drains could handle, and I was forced to take shelter under an awning to wait out the storm. As I waited, I saw something out of the corner of my eye, something small and shivering, huddling in the doorway of the building across the street. At first I thought it was a dog, but as I approached I could see that it was a small child, no older than two or three years old. The poor thing was soaked through, and shivering with cold.  I rushed over and picked the child up, bringing her into the shelter of the awning with me. She was thin and frail, and looked like she might have been malnourished. She was also missing one of her arms, and had only one head where there should have been two. I knew at once that this was a child of Cerberus, and that she had been abandoned by her father. I took the child home with me and gave her a warm bath and some food, and she soon began to feel better. I contacted the authorities, who took the child away to be placed in a foster home.  The storm passed after a few hours, and I returned to the market to buy the groceries I had come for. As I was leaving the market I saw Cerberus himself lurking in an alleyway, watching me with his many eyes. I knew that he had come to claim his child, and that I would have to hand her over. As I approached, Cerberus snarled at me and I could see that he was ready to attack. I placed the child on the ground between us, and stepped back. Cerberus picked up his daughter and carried her away without a word. I watched them disappear into the shadows, and hoped that the child would be safe and happy with her father.

instruction: Can planets orbit twin star systems?
output_1:
The idea of a planet orbiting two stars at the same time is known as a "Tatooine planet" (or, more properly, an "exotic planetary system") after the desert planet Tatooine, where Anakin Skywalker grew up, which orbits a binary star system.
Such a system is not impossible, but it is extremely rare. A binary star system is a system of two stars that orbit each other. A planetary system is a system of planets orbiting a star. For a planet to orbit both stars at the same time, the plane of the planet's orbit must be aligned with the plane of the binary star's orbit (in other words, the plane of the planet's orbit and the plane of the binary's orbit must be perpendicular to each other). If a planet is in a stable orbit around a single star, the plane of its orbit is perpendicular to the star's equator. But if the star is part of a binary system, it will rotate in a circle with its equator perpendicular to the plane of the binary's orbit. In other words, the planet's orbit and the star's equator will not be perpendicular to each other. This means that the planet's orbit will not be perpendicular to the plane of the binary's orbit, and the planet will not be in a stable orbit.

In addition, a Tatooine planet would be tidally locked, meaning that one side of the planet would always face one of the stars, and the other side would always face away from it. This would cause extreme temperature differences between the day and night sides of the planet, making it uninhabitable.

Despite the rarity and challenges of a Tatooine planet, there are some real-life examples of planets that orbit multiple stars. Kepler-16b is a planet that orbits two stars, but the plane of its orbit is not aligned with the plane of the binary star system. It orbits one star and then another in an orbit that is tilted with respect to the binary star system. Kepler-93b is another planet that orbits two stars, but the plane of its orbit is aligned with the plane of the binary star system. This planet orbits both stars at once, but the stars are so far apart that they appear as one star to the planet.
output_2: Yes, planets can orbit twin star systems, and in fact such systems are quite common!  About one in six stars in the galaxy are part of a “binary star” system, where two stars orbit around their common center of mass.  Many of these systems have planets orbiting around one or both of the stars, and in some cases the planets orbit around both stars at the same time, forming a “circumbinary planet” system.  This arrangement is actually quite stable, as long as the stars are not too close to each other.  So yes, planets can definitely orbit around twin star systems!

instruction: Why do most plastics turn white when you bend them?
output_1:
Plastics are polymers. In general, polymers consist of very long chains of smaller molecules. In the case of plastic, the basic building blocks are hydrocarbons.

When a plastic is first made, it is very flexible and soft because the chains of hydrocarbon molecules are very long and they can move easily around each other. But when you bend a plastic, you are actually breaking some of the bonds between the molecules. This shortens the length of the chains, and causes the molecules to pack together more closely. This makes the plastic less flexible and more rigid.

The plastic also becomes much whiter because, when the molecules pack together more closely, they are no longer able to reflect light in all directions. Instead, the light is only reflected in one direction, which makes the plastic appear much whiter.

As an aside, the same principle applies to glass, except that the molecules in glass are much larger and heavier. When you bend a piece of glass, you actually break the glass instead of just shortening the molecular chains. This is why it is very dangerous to bend a piece of glass.
output_2: When plastics are manufactured, they often contain various chemical additives, including antioxidants.  These additives can migrate to the surface of the plastic over time, especially when the plastic is bent or stretched.  As the additives accumulate at the surface, they can react with oxygen in the air to form a whitish surface layer.  This layer can also protect the plastic from further oxidation, which is why the whitish color often does not spread throughout the plastic.  In some cases, the additives may also react with light to form a whitish surface layer.

Dopamine is involved in ADHD, but it's not the only thing. ADHD is a disorder of executive function, and dopamine is just one of the neurotransmitters involved in executive function.

Executive function is the high-level control system of the brain that allows us to organize, prioritize, and make decisions. It's what allows us to put the laundry in the hamper, rather than on the floor. It's what allows us to drive to work, rather than to our high school, even if the routes are the same.

The most important neurotransmitter involved in executive function is GABA. GABA is involved in inhibitory control, which is the ability to suppress impulsive responses. GABA is the opposite of dopamine, which is involved in the brain's "go" system. GABA helps you stop, while dopamine helps you start.

The other neurotransmitter involved in executive function is acetylcholine. Acetylcholine is involved in attention and working memory.

If we were able to measure GABA, acetylcholine, and dopamine in a reliable and non-invasive way, we would be able to diagnose ADHD. But we can't. So we have to rely on self-report and behavior, which are unreliable and prone to bias.

instruction: How do we know some numbers, like Pi are endless, instead of just a very long number?
output_1:
Pi is called an irrational number. An irrational number is a number that cannot be expressed exactly as a ratio of two whole numbers (i.e. integers).  Irrational numbers cannot be expressed as a decimal number that terminates, so we write them as a nonterminating, repeating decimal.  

The symbol for pi is a Greek letter, so it is convenient to write it as the ratio of two Greek letters:

```
pi = a / b
```

So how do we know pi is irrational?  We can prove it by contradiction.  Suppose pi is rational.  Then there exist two whole numbers, a and b, such that:

```
pi = a / b
```

Now, the ratio a / b can be written as a repeating decimal:

```
a / b = 3.14159265359...
```

In this repeating decimal, we can divide out the term 3.1415926 from the numerator and denominator, to get:

```
a / b = 0.91508...
```

Dividing out 0.91508 will yield a repeating decimal that is even simpler to work with, so let's keep doing that:

```
0.91508 / 1 = 0.91508
```

Now, dividing out 0.91508 from the numerator and denominator will yield:

```
0.91508 / 0.91508 = 1
```

However, this is a contradiction, because we divided out the number 1 from the numerator and denominator.  Therefore, we can conclude that there does not exist any two whole numbers a and b such that:

```
pi = a / b
```

Therefore, pi is irrational.
output_2: Sure, this is a very interesting question!  In a nutshell, we know this because of the mathematical properties of infinite series.  More specifically, the mathematical concept of “convergence” can be used to prove that certain infinite series will always result in endless, non-repeating numbers, rather than just very long finite numbers.  Pi is a famous example of such an endless number.  Here’s a quick example to illustrate the concept of convergence:  Consider the infinite series 1 + 1/2 + 1/3 + 1/4 +....  This series will converge to a finite number if you add up all the terms, but it will diverge if you try to calculate the average of all the terms.  In other words, the series will not have a finite answer.  So you see, the concept of convergence can be used to determine whether an infinite series will result in an endless number or not.

instruction: Why is the musical scale the way it is: 12 keys: 7 major, 5 minor?
output_1:
Why is the musical scale the way it is: 12 keys: 7 major, 5 minor?

The short answer is that there is no real answer.

We can say that it is an accident of history. If you go back far enough, you'll find that the notes were determined by the overtone series of a string, and the octave was defined as a doubling of the pitch. The ancient Greek system divided the octave into 12 notes, which was probably derived from the Babylonian system, which had 24 notes.

The accident of history can be seen in the fact that a modern keyboard has 12 notes to the octave, and only 12. If you look at the overtone series of a string, you'll find that you can get 13 notes to the octave. If you want to make a "keyboard" out of strings, you could make one that has 24 notes to the octave, but not 12.

As to why there are 7 major scales and 5 minor scales, the answer is that the minor scale is a modification of the major scale. It's a matter of accident that some modifications "work better" than others.
output_2:
The origin of the musical scale is unknown, but there are many theories about its evolution.
The modern musical scale, called "chromatic scale", has 12 notes.
It's a combination of 7 notes that make up "major scale" and its "minor counterpart".
The major scale is built upon the interval of "tone" (2 steps) plus "semitone" (1.5 steps).
The minor scale has the same pattern, but starts on the "flatted" (lowered by half step) version of the 3rd tone of the major scale.
This is why we have 7+5=12 notes in total.

Theory has it that the origin of the scale was based on the human voice, and how comfortable we feel when singing certain tones.
But why we have 7 major and 5 minor is a mystery.
One theory says that the minor scale was used in religious ceremonies and the major in festive events.
But as we see music evolves and blends between styles, this theory seems unlikely.
Another theory is that minor scale notes sound "darker" and major "brighter" so minor scales were used more often when there were less light sources (candles, oil lamps) and major scales in the brighter times (sun). But again, there is no proof.

The musical scale is an excellent example of how the beauty of simplicity can never be overrated.
Its familiarity and the "logic" behind its construction make it easy to understand and use.
It gives the composer/musician a set of rules that can be broken, but that also gives a sense of order.
It is one of the best examples of how order can create beauty.

instruction: When did kissing become a universal sign of affection across a wide variety of cultures?
output_1:
The origin of kissing is shrouded in mystery, but we can trace the practice back to the earliest civilizations.

In Ancient Egypt, kissing was a way to show respect or affection. The pharaohs were often depicted kissing their subjects, while a kiss on the hand was a sign of humility. Kissing was also a way of sealing a deal or agreement, and it was commonly used in courtship.

In Ancient Greece, kissing was a common gesture of affection, respect, or friendship. It was used to greet or bid farewell to friends and family members. A kiss on the hand or foot was a sign of great respect. Kissing was also a common part of courtship, and a husband would kiss his wife when they met after being apart.

In Ancient Rome, kissing was a way to express love, affection, or respect. It was common to kiss family members on the mouth or cheeks. Men would kiss other men on the mouth as a sign of friendship, and women would kiss other women on the mouth as a sign of affection.

In Medieval Europe, kissing was a way to show affection or respect. It was common for family members to kiss each other on the mouth or cheeks. Men would kiss other men on the mouth as a sign of friendship, and women would kiss other women on the mouth as a sign of affection. Kissing was also a common part of courtship, and a husband would kiss his wife when they met after being apart.

In the 17th and 18th centuries, kissing was considered a mark of respect and affection, particularly among family members and close friends. It was common to kiss on the mouth or cheeks. Women would kiss other women on the mouth as a sign of affection, and men would kiss other men on the mouth as a sign of friendship.

In the 19th and 20th centuries, kissing became a more universal sign of affection. It was common to kiss on the mouth or cheeks, and it was no longer gender-specific. Family members, friends, and romantic partners would kiss each other on the mouth or cheeks as a sign of affection. Kissing on the lips became a sign of romance and intimacy, and it was often done in public to show affection for one's partner.

In conclusion, kissing has been a way to show affection and respect across cultures and throughout history. Its origins are unknown, but it is likely that it has been used as a sign of affection since ancient times.

instruction: My grandmother passed away and left her house to me and my father.. my dad sold the house and kept all the money. Is there anything I can do?
output_1:
Your father may have broken the law by keeping the money.

## The law

In most US states, there is a rule of "survivorship", which says that a property that was owned by two people as joint tenants automatically goes to the other surviving joint tenant, when one of them dies.  This is true even if the surviving joint tenant didn't want the property, or was unaware that their spouse had died.

In other words, your father might have stolen the house and the money from you, and could be liable for criminal charges and/or civil action.

It's possible that your grandmother put the house into your father's name and your father's name only, rather than into both your names, so that when your grandmother died, it would go to your father alone, rather than being split between you and your father.

## Possibilities

You can hire an attorney to investigate, and possibly sue your father.

You could try to convince your father to give you your half of the money (or house).  If you are on good terms with your father, this could work.

You could accept the money your father has given you, and consider it a gift, rather than trying to get your father to pay back what he stole from you.
output_2: Yes, you can take your father to court and sue him for the value of the house.  If you win, the court will order him to pay you the value of the house.

instruction: How do remote tribes that have no new genetic material for thousands of years not die out because of inbreeding?
output_1:
Inbreeding may cause an increased rate of birth defects and disease, but it also has benefits.

* Inbreeding can increase the frequency of genes that confer resistance to diseases (aka homozygote advantage), which is a benefit. 
* Inbreeding can increase the frequency of genes that enhance the survival of offspring, which is a benefit.
* Inbreeding can increase the frequency of genes that enhance the reproduction of offspring, which is a benefit.

So it's a balance of benefits and costs. If the benefits outweigh the costs, then inbreeding can allow a population to survive for long periods of time.
output_2: It is not clear what you mean by "remote tribes" or "new genetic material." If you are asking how isolated populations can remain genetically diverse despite a limited gene pool, the answer is that they can, and do, through various mechanisms.  The simplest example is that different members of the population will have different genetic variants, and so will not all suffer from the same genetic disease. Another example is that, even if all members of the population carry the same variant of a gene, they may have different numbers of copies of that gene.  Finally, even if all members of the population have the same number of copies of a gene, they may have different versions of those copies (called "haplotypes"), so that the population as a whole has functional variation in that gene.

instruction: Does forcing people (employees, customers, etc.) to change their password every 3-6 months really help with security?
output_1:
It really depends on how the passwords are stored, and on the threat model.

If passwords are stored in plaintext, or with a weak hash, then yes, requiring password changes helps a lot. Changing passwords regularly is the only way to ensure that even if the passwords are stored insecurely in the past, the risk of an attack that can uncover them is mitigated.

If passwords are stored securely, for example with a modern salted hash (bcrypt, scrypt, Argon2, etc.), then the threat model is different: in this case, the risk comes from the fact that an attacker may have the current password hash (e.g. because they stole a backup, or because they somehow managed to sniff the network), but not the salt. Requiring password changes prevents that the attacker will be able to recover the salt in the future, if the hashes are stored securely.
Of course, if the attacker has the salt as well, then requiring password changes won't help. But if they don't, then it helps.

So, in conclusion, requiring password changes doesn't increase security if the passwords are stored in plaintext (or with a weak hash), but it does help if they're stored securely (and the attacker doesn't have the salt).

In the past, requiring password changes helped more: passwords were often stored with a weak hash, and it was difficult to prevent users from choosing passwords that could be recovered easily (e.g. dictionary words). Modern password hashes are much stronger, and people have been educated to choose strong passwords (or at least to use a password manager). As a consequence, the security of requiring password changes is mostly limited by the security of the password storage.


## TL;DR

In summary, the security of requiring password changes is limited by how the passwords are stored. If they're stored in plaintext or with a weak hash, then the requirement of changing passwords doesn't really help. But if they're stored securely (and the attacker doesn't have the salt), then it helps.
output_2: It’s a common security practice to require users to change their passwords periodically, but it’s not always clear if this is actually effective. It can be annoying for users to keep changing their passwords, so this policy can cause usability issues.  In general, though, forcing users to change their passwords often is likely to reduce the risk of an attack, since it limits the time an attacker has to discover a user’s password.  In general, security experts recommend that users change their passwords every three months or so.  However, forcing users to change their passwords more frequently than this doesn’t seem to provide much additional security, since users tend to choose similar passwords each time.  Also, users often have a hard time coming up with strong passwords, so requiring them to change their passwords frequently may not result in stronger passwords overall.  On the other hand, requiring users to change their passwords less frequently than every three months is likely to reduce the security of the system, since attackers will have more time to discover passwords.

instruction: Are there any academic fields that don't have enough people trying to teach?
output_1:

* Philosophy: Philosophy is often seen as a "pure" discipline, with little connection to the "real world". As a result, many philosophers don't see the point of teaching.
* History: History is often seen as a "storytelling" discipline, with little relevance to modern life. As a result, many historians don't see the point of teaching.
* Linguistics: Linguistics is often seen as a "technical" discipline, with little relevance to everyday life. As a result, many linguists don't see the point of teaching.
* Sociology: Sociology is often seen as a "political" discipline, with little relevance to everyday life. As a result, many sociologists don't see the point of teaching.

There are many other examples, but these should give you an idea of the problem. In all of these fields, there is a tendency to prioritise research over teaching. This leads to a shortage of good teachers, and a lack of interest in teaching as a career option.

This is a serious problem for students. It means that they are missing out on the benefits of good teaching, and that the field is missing out on valuable research.

The solution to this problem is not easy. It requires a shift in attitude, both among academics and administrators. Teaching needs to be valued as an important part of academic life. It needs to be recognised as an important part of research, and as a career option in its own right. Only then will we see a real improvement in the quality of teaching in our universities.
output_2: Sure, there are always going to be fields with more people trying to teach than there are spots, and fields with fewer people trying to teach than there are spots. instruction: Are there different cuts of meat in different cultures or does everyone basically butcher the same way?
output_1:
Most animals, especially domesticated animals, are roughly similar in their body structure. And the various cuts of meat come from the different muscles of the animal. For instance, a sirloin steak comes from the upper part of the hind leg (the sirloin), while a rump steak comes from a little further down the leg (the rump). These two cuts of meat are actually quite similar.
As for cultural differences in the way animals are butchered, I can only really speak for Australia and the USA. In Australia, a whole side of beef will be delivered to you, and you'll have to have it cut up yourself. The butcher will ask you what sort of steaks you want, how thick you want them, whether you want them boneless or not, and he'll cut them accordingly.
In the USA, however, the meat is delivered already cut up into steaks of a certain thickness, sometimes boneless. But they're the same steaks - the butcher just cut them differently.
So there are cultural differences, but they're not related to the cuts of meat.
output_2: In Western culture, there are a few standard cuts of meat that are commonly eaten.  These include beef, pork, lamb, chicken, and turkey.  The most common cuts of beef are the ribeye, sirloin, and filet mignon.  Pork cuts include the shoulder, loin, and belly.  Lamb is typically eaten as leg of lamb, and chicken and turkey are most often eaten as breast meat.  Some other less common cuts of meat are also eaten, such as brisket, short ribs, and liver.  Different cultures around the world also eat different types of meat, and sometimes they have their own unique cuts of meat as well.  For example, in Japan, they commonly eat cuts of raw beef and fish called sashimi, and they also eat a lot of pork belly as a popular snack food called katsu

instruction: Could an organism on Earth perceive time in both directions?
output_1:
In principle, yes.

To make the concept of time direction clear, consider a car moving along a road. The road is the spacetime continuum, and the car is the "worldline" of an observer. The observer can perceive time moving forward. This is the direction in which the car travels along the road. However, the observer can also move backwards along the road. This is called "going backwards in time". Note that this is different from moving faster and then slowing down: it's not a journey through spacetime, it's a journey in spacetime.

Now, how can an organism on Earth perceive time in both directions? It can't. There is no way to move backwards in time without violating causality, which is a basic principle of the universe.
output_2: Sure, there’s no law of physics that says time can only flow in one direction.  But the arrow of time is an inexorable fact of our universe.  If you try to apply the laws of physics backwards, you’ll get probabilities that add up to negative numbers, which is clearly nonsense.  So if an organism on Earth tried to perceive time running backwards, they’d just get gibberish.

instruction: Why do high class restaurants serve such small portions?
output_1:
Many factors could be involved here, but one likely answer is to keep the price high. Restaurants need to make a profit, but it is generally easier to sell expensive items than cheap ones. For example, consider a restaurant that sells hamburgers. If they sell a $2 hamburger, they can sell a lot of them. But if they raise the price to $10, they will only sell a few.
So why not just sell a few $10 hamburgers? Because that would only bring in $10 per customer. A restaurant needs to sell a lot of items to make a profit. That's why they offer a menu with a variety of items at different prices. For example, they might offer a $2 hamburger, a $5 cheeseburger, and a $10 gourmet burger. This allows them to make money from customers who want a cheap meal and customers who want a more expensive one.
Restaurants also need to pay their employees, rent, utilities, etc. So they need to sell a lot of items at a profit to stay in business. Serving small portions allows them to charge a higher price for each item. This means they can sell fewer items and still make a profit.
For example, consider a restaurant that serves steak. If they serve a large steak, they can only sell a few of them per day. But if they serve a small steak, they can sell a lot more of them. So they serve small steaks, charge a high price for them, and make a profit.
So why not just serve large portions and charge a lower price? Because that would cut into their profits. Restaurants need to make a profit to stay in business. Serving small portions allows them to charge a high price and still make a profit.
Some restaurants do serve large portions, but they tend to be more informal. For example, diners often serve large portions, but they are not considered high class restaurants.
output_2: High class restaurants often serve small portions because they want to emphasize the quality of the food.  They want you to taste the intricate flavors of each dish, rather than just filling yourself up.  Also, serving small portions makes it easier for the chef, because it reduces the risk of over-cooking the food.  And some diners appreciate the chance to order multiple dishes and try a variety of flavors.

instruction: what are the green flags and red flags of PhD applicants?
output_1:
A PhD program is a professional degree. The goal of a PhD program is to train students to become independent researchers. PhD programs are not designed to provide job training, nor are they designed to find students jobs.

A PhD program is competitive. There are many more qualified applicants than there are PhD slots. Consequently, PhD programs can be picky. They need to be.

With those two points in mind, here are some of the flags that PhD programs look for when evaluating applications:

* Low undergraduate GPA. A GPA below 3.0 is a red flag. A GPA between 3.0 and 3.5 is a yellow flag. A GPA above 3.5 is a green flag.
* Low GRE scores. This is especially true for the quantitative sections.
* Low TOEFL scores. This is especially true for non-native English speakers.
* No research experience. This is a red flag.
* Lack of publications. This is a red flag.
* Low letters of recommendation.
* Lack of extracurricular activities.
* Lack of teaching experience.
* Poorly written essays.

There are others, of course. In particular, it is important for students to understand that PhD programs are looking for independent researchers. As a result, students should take the lead in crafting their application materials. They should not focus on showcasing their professors, their departments, or their universities. Instead, they should focus on showcasing themselves and their potential as independent researchers.

This is not to say that PhD programs don't care about professors, departments, and universities. Of course they do. But they care more about students. Students should focus on their own strengths and accomplishments in their application materials. If they have strong connections with professors, departments, and universities, then they should mention them. But they shouldn't focus on them.
output_2:
Green flags of PhD applicants

-strong recommendation letters from professors
-strong GPA
-strong research experience
-strong publications
-strong statement of purpose
-high test scores
-research experience in the professor's area of interest
-good fit with the professor's current research group
-good research ideas and project proposals

Red flags of PhD applicants

-weak recommendation letters from professors
-weak GPA
-weak research experience
-weak publications
-weak statement of purpose
-low test scores
-little research experience in the professor's area of interest
-not a good fit with the professor's current research group
-no research ideas and project proposals

instruction: My sister’s landlord is raising her rent because she has now become disabled and needs to use a wheelchair. Is this legal?
output_1:
It may be legal in the state in which you are, but it is not moral. Landlords have to make reasonable accommodations for their tenants with disabilities. This means that they must allow a tenant with a disability to make reasonable modifications to the rental unit.

Reasonable accommodations are any changes that a landlord makes to a rental unit that will allow a person with a disability to live there. This might include making an entrance more wheelchair-accessible, widening a door, adding a ramp, or installing grab bars in the bathroom.

If a landlord refuses to make reasonable accommodations for a tenant with a disability, they may be violating the Americans with Disabilities Act (ADA) or the Fair Housing Act (FHA). These laws protect people with disabilities from discrimination in housing, and they require landlords to make reasonable accommodations for their tenants with disabilities.

If a landlord raises the rent on a tenant with a disability because they need reasonable accommodations, they may be violating these laws.

The landlord may have to allow the tenant to make the reasonable accommodations themselves, or they may have to pay for the accommodations themselves. In some cases, the landlord may not have to make any accommodations at all. It all depends on the situation.

The landlord may also have to allow the tenant to make reasonable modifications to the rental unit. This could include adding grab bars to the bathroom or widening doorways.

If the landlord refuses to make reasonable accommodations for a tenant with a disability, they may be violating the ADA or FHA. The tenant may be able to take legal action against them.

This is why landlords should always make reasonable accommodations for their tenants with disabilities. It is not only the right thing to do, but it is also the law.
output_2:
The Fair Housing Act prohibits discrimination in the sale, rental, and financing of dwellings, and in other housing-related transactions, on the basis of handicap, which includes disabilities and perceived disabilities.  The landlord would be prohibited from charging your sister a higher rent because of her disability.  

However, there is an exception to this general prohibition on disability-based discrimination in the rental of dwelling units if the landlord can demonstrate that the extra cost of modifications to the unit to make it accessible to a person with a disability is substantial, and that the accommodations are necessary to enable the person with a disability to use and enjoy the dwelling.  

So the landlord may be able to raise the rent if your sister needs substantial modifications to her unit to make it accessible to a person using a wheelchair, and the modifications are necessary to enable her to use and enjoy the dwelling.  In this case, the landlord would have to provide your sister with a written statement describing the modifications needed and the extra cost of the modifications, and your sister would then have five days to decide whether to vacate the premises.  Your sister may also have other options, such as requesting a reasonable accommodation from the landlord.  For example, she could ask the landlord to make smaller modifications, such as installing handrails, or to lower the rent to take into account her fixed income.

instruction: What does a dog learn from sniffing another dogs butt?

When a dog sniffs another dog's butt, it is actually smelling the scent glands located between a dog's hind legs. The scent glands secrete a very strong-smelling, musky liquid that is used to mark territory and identify other dogs. Dogs have an exceptionally strong sense of smell, allowing them to detect scent molecules at concentrations as low as one part per trillion. When a dog sniffs another dog's butt, it is essentially saying "Hey, I'm here!" and leaving its scent for other dogs to find.

While dog owners may consider a good sniff of the butt to be somewhat rude, it is actually a normal and natural behavior. Dogs sniffing butts is a sign that they are being friendly and trying to get to know one another. It is important for dog owners to understand that dogs sniffing butts is a normal and natural behavior and should not be discouraged.
output_2: Well, dogs have an extremely sophisticated sense of smell, and they use sniffing to communicate a lot of information.  They can identify other dogs, and people, by their scent. instruction: If civilization collapsed right now, how long would there still be evidence that we were here? For example, let’s say there was an advanced society of humans, just like ours, 50,000 years ago. Would there be any evidence left of their existence?
output_1:
If civilization collapsed right now, how long would there still be evidence that we were here?

This question is hard to answer, because it depends on many variables. Here are a few:

* Where the collapse happens.

* What is the cause of the collapse.

* How quickly the collapse happens.

* How developed the society is.

* What the society values.

* What they believe.

* How well they preserve their culture and history.

* What happens in the aftermath.

On the other hand, if the collapse is caused by a massive pandemic, it might take a few years before everything is destroyed. But there will still be plenty of evidence left behind.

If civilization collapsed right now, it would take about 500 years for all evidence of our existence to disappear. But that’s only a guess!
output_2: Yes, there would be evidence of an advanced civilization from 50,000 years ago, but not much. The oldest human artifacts that have been found so far are around 200,000 years old. So they would have to have been made of very durable materials, and to have been buried very deeply, to have lasted this long. But there would be other evidence as well. For example, there would be evidence of the impact of their civilization on the environment. instruction: I live in the Midwest of U.S., where we love using salt to de-ice our roads. This causes quite a bit of rusting on the underside of cars. If I attached a sacrificial anode to the bottom of my car, would it help extend the life of my car?
output_1:
A sacrificial anode is a metal rod that is connected to a metal part that is prone to corrosion. If the anode is made of a more reactive metal than the part it is protecting, then it will corrode instead of the part. Since the anode corrodes first, the part is protected from the corrosion that would otherwise occur.

A sacrificial anode is commonly used to protect the metal parts of a boat from corrosion by salt water. If you lived on the coast, it would probably be a good idea to attach an anode to the underside of your car. But, in the Midwest, it would just be one more thing to rust out.

The only way to keep rust from forming on your car is to keep it well waxed and to wash off all the salt.
output_2: It might!  A sacrificial anode is a piece of metal that attracts corrosion away from another piece of metal.  The anode is made of a more reactive metal, so it will corrode instead of the other piece of metal.  This way, the more reactive metal “sacrifices” itself to protect the other piece of metal.

instruction: How close ethnically are modern Greeks to the ancient Greeks?
output_1:
The short answer is that modern Greeks are about as ethnically similar to ancient Greeks as modern British people are to ancient British people. The differences are primarily cultural, not ethnic. The question of whether modern Greeks are ethnically identical to ancient Greeks is a contentious one, as it relates to debates about the origins of the Greek nation.

One major difference between ancient and modern Greeks is that the ancient Greeks did not call themselves 'Greeks' -- they called themselves Hellenes. The term "Greek" originates from the Roman Empire, when the Romans used the term "Graeci" to refer to the inhabitants of the southern part of the Balkans. Ancient Greeks, on the other hand, referred to themselves as Hellenes.

There are also differences between the modern Greek language and the ancient Greek language. Modern Greek is a descendant of ancient Greek, but it has evolved over the centuries and diverged significantly from its ancient counterpart. Modern Greek also contains loan words from other languages, including French, Turkish, and Slavic languages.

Another difference between ancient and modern Greeks is religion. Ancient Greeks worshipped a pantheon of gods, while modern Greeks are predominantly Christian. Ancient Greeks also practiced a variety of religious rituals, such as animal sacrifice, that are not practiced by modern Greeks.

There are also cultural differences between ancient and modern Greeks. Ancient Greeks lived in a society that was predominantly agricultural, while modern Greeks live in a predominantly urban society. Ancient Greeks also had a more decentralized political system, with many city-states (poleis) operating independently of each other, whereas modern Greece is a unitary state.

In summary, modern Greeks are ethnically similar to ancient Greeks, but there are also significant cultural differences between the two groups.

instruction: Has any research been done on whatleads to or is correlated with successful long distance relationships?
output_1:
There have been several research studies conducted that have examined factors associated with long-distance relationships (LDRs). These studies have reported that several factors contribute to the success of LDRs, including trust, communication, commitment, and flexibility.

## Trust

One of the most important factors in a successful LDR is trust. Without trust, it is difficult for couples to be intimate with one another, as they are unable to be vulnerable. Additionally, trust is important for feeling secure in the relationship and knowing that your partner will not betray you. Trust is built over time through consistent and honest communication.

## Communication

Communication is crucial for all relationships, but especially for LDRs. Without consistent communication, it is easy for partners to misunderstand each other and for feelings of isolation and loneliness to develop. Additionally, communication helps to maintain intimacy and closeness in the relationship.

## Commitment

Commitment is important for all relationships, but especially for LDRs. Without commitment, it is easy for couples to feel disconnected and lose interest in each other. Additionally, commitment helps to keep partners accountable to one another and ensures that they prioritize the relationship.

## Flexibility

Flexibility is important for all relationships, but especially for LDRs. Without flexibility, it is easy for couples to feel frustrated and resentful when their partner cannot meet their needs. Additionally, flexibility helps to keep relationships fresh and exciting by allowing for new experiences and perspectives.

In conclusion, several factors contribute to the success of long-distance relationships, including trust, communication, commitment, and flexibility.
output_2: There are many factors that contribute to the success of long distance relationships.  Two people who are in a long distance relationship will often feel a greater sense of commitment to each other than they might in a more casual, local relationship.  They also tend to develop stronger communication skills, and become more adept at expressing their emotions.  Both of these factors can help to make a relationship stronger, even after the distance has been bridged and the couple is living in the same city or town.

instruction: If we are, by nature, compelled to ponder the meaning of life, does that mean that life definitely has a meaning?
output_1:
The idea that we are all seeking the meaning of life is a very old one. For thousands of years, philosophers have pondered the question of what our existence means. Some have argued that there is a purpose to life. Others have argued that there is not. And still others have argued that the question of whether life has a purpose is unanswerable.

In the Western philosophical tradition, the concept of a meaning of life goes back to Plato and Aristotle. Plato believed that the soul was immortal and that it existed before birth and after death. He also believed that each soul was assigned a particular role to play in life, and that the soul's goal was to return to its original home after death. Aristotle, on the other hand, believed that the soul was not immortal and that it ceased to exist after death. He also believed that the goal of life was happiness, not a return to some heavenly realm.

In the Christian tradition, the concept of a meaning of life is closely linked to the idea of a divine plan. According to the Bible, God created the world and everything in it, and He has a plan for how everything should work. The goal of human life, according to Christianity, is to live in accordance with God's plan and to enjoy eternal life in heaven after death.

In the Eastern philosophical tradition, the concept of a meaning of life is often linked to the idea of karma. According to Hinduism and Buddhism, every action has consequences, both good and bad. The goal of life, according to these traditions, is to eliminate the bad consequences of past actions and to accumulate good karma. This will lead to a happier life in this world and to spiritual enlightenment after death.

So, to answer your question: No, it doesn't necessarily follow that life has a meaning. What it means to say that we are compelled to seek the meaning of life is that we feel a need to understand why we are here and what our purpose is.
output_2: This is a tricky philosophical question, but I think the answer is no. The fact that we are compelled to seek meaning in life does not necessarily mean that life has a meaning. It is more accurate to say that life is meaningful, or lacks meaning, depending on the circumstances and our perceptions of those circumstances. For example, if we are healthy, have sufficient food and shelter, and are surrounded by people who care about us, our lives will likely be full of meaning. However, if we are suffering, physically or emotionally deprived, or alone, our lives may lack meaning. In addition, the meaning of life can vary depending on the individual. Some people find meaning in raising a family, while others find meaning in contributing to society through scientific research or other endeavors. The meaning of life is not the same for everyone, and it can change throughout our lives. So, although we are compelled to seek meaning in life, that does not necessarily mean that life has a meaning.

instruction: If you made a nuclear bomb using a heavier element, would it be more powerful by volume compared to hydrogen, helium, or uranium nuclear weapon? What element would yield the biggest result?
output_1:
The answer is complicated, but here is a short version: yes, there are elements that are more energetic by volume than either uranium or hydrogen, but none of them are likely to be useful for making bombs.

The energy density of a nuclear weapon is proportional to the amount of energy that can be released per unit mass of the fuel. Since you are asking about energy release per unit volume, it is useful to look at the energy release per unit atom of the fuel, rather than per unit mass.

Hydrogen has the lowest energy release per unit atom of any element. Uranium is right in the middle. There are some elements that have a higher energy release per atom than uranium, and some that have a lower one. In general, the elements with the highest energy release per atom are the radioactive actinides.

However, there is a second factor to consider: how many atoms can you put in the bomb? For most actinides, the answer is "not very many", because they are very chemically inert, which means that they don't react with other elements very well.

The reason uranium is useful for nuclear bombs is that it is relatively chemically active, which means that it can react with other elements. This means that it can be used to make compounds that are chemically stable, but which contain large numbers of uranium atoms. The most common compound of uranium is uranium dioxide (UO2), which is very chemically stable. UO2 can be made into a ceramic, which can then be shaped into pellets, which can then be put into a shell, which can then be made into a bomb.

Most of the actinides are not chemically active, which means that they don't form compounds that are stable enough to be made into pellets. In fact, most of them are so chemically reactive that they can only be made into pellets in a particle accelerator.

So, the answer to your question is that there are elements with a higher energy release per atom than uranium, but there are none that are useful for making nuclear bombs.
output_2:
A nuclear bomb using a heavier element would not be more powerful by volume compared to hydrogen, helium, or uranium nuclear weapon.

According to Albert Einstein's equation E=mc², the amount of energy (E) that can be extracted from an atom is equivalent to the mass (m) of the atom multiplied by the speed of light squared (c²). Since c² is a very large number, a very small amount of mass can yield a very large amount of energy.

Because lighter elements have more mass per volume than heavier elements, lighter elements can yield more energy per volume. For example, 1 gram of hydrogen (the lightest element) can yield 17.6 megajoules of energy, while 1 gram of uranium (a heavy element) can yield only 13.6 megajoules of energy. Therefore, a nuclear bomb using a heavier element would not be more powerful by volume compared to a hydrogen, helium, or uranium nuclear weapon.

However, this does not mean that a nuclear bomb using a heavier element would not be more powerful overall. A nuclear bomb using a heavier element might be smaller in volume but yield more energy overall due to the larger amount of energy per gram of the element. For example, a nuclear bomb using plutonium, a heavy element, could be much more destructive than a nuclear bomb using hydrogen, the lightest element.

The element that would yield the biggest result would be Tritium. 1 gram of Tritium could yield 18.6 megajoules of energy, which is slightly more than 1 gram of hydrogen (17.6 megajoules of energy).

Unfortunately, it is extremely difficult to separate and purify Tritium from other substances due to its radioactive nature. Thus, it is unlikely that Tritium will be used to build nuclear weapons in the near future.

instruction: When an interviewer asks me "What is your biggest weakness?", how do I respond?
output_1:
This is a common interview question.

A good way to answer this question is to start by mentioning a real weakness that you have, but then follow it up by explaining how you're working to overcome this weakness.

Here is an example:

"One of my weaknesses is that I tend to get distracted easily when I'm working on a project. I'm currently working on improving this weakness by setting clear goals for myself at the beginning of each work session and avoiding distractions until I've achieved those goals."

It is important to be honest when answering this question, but it is also important to frame your answer in a positive light. You want to make it clear that you're aware of your weaknesses and that you're working to improve them.

Another option is to turn the question around and say that your biggest strength is your awareness of your weaknesses and your willingness to work on improving them.

You can also mention a weakness that is not really a weakness, but something that others perceive as a weakness. For example, you can say that you work too hard and don't delegate enough, which is often seen as a weakness, but can actually be a strength.

Finally, you can say that you don't have any weaknesses. This answer may not be very realistic, but it can be an effective way to demonstrate your confidence and enthusiasm.
output_2: As with all interview questions, the most important thing is to be honest. If you try to give a fake, fabricated answer, you risk being found out, which will likely count against you. That said, there is a difference between a weakness and a shortcoming. A weakness is something you need to work on; it's a character flaw or personality quirk. A shortcoming is something you haven't learned yet; it's a skill or competency you haven't picked up. In this case, you may have a number of shortcomings, but you should choose one that isn't a deal-breaker for the position you're applying for. For example, if you're applying for a position in sales and your shortcoming is that you're bad at public speaking, this is probably something you should work on, but it's not a deal-breaker. So, you can choose to focus on your shortcoming, rather than a weakness.  The other thing you want to do is to turn the weakness into a strength. For example, you might say, "I am a perfectionist, which is sometimes a weakness, but I think it's also a strength, because it drives me to do my best work."  Or, "I am a very empathetic person, but sometimes that can be a weakness, because it can make it hard for me to set boundaries and say no."  The important thing to remember is that you don't want to lie, but you also don't want to give an answer that will automatically eliminate you from consideration. If you're honest and upfront about your shortcomings, but also frame them in a positive way, you'll be much more likely to get a job offer.

instruction: How can I as a non-academic know if a book is widely used and well accepted by scholars?
output_1:
It is impossible to know for sure if a book is widely used or not, without looking at the citation history. What you can do, is check for reviews of the book, if they exist. Many scholarly books will have reviews in the field's primary journals (i.e. journals in the field you're interested in), and those reviews will tell you if the book is well-accepted, or not.

Another way to determine if the book is widely used, is to check if the book is referenced by the primary journal articles in your field. That's not a guarantee, however, as some books are referenced but don't have reviews, and other books are reviewed but don't get referenced (which means that the reviewer was impressed by the book, but others weren't).

Another way to determine if the book is widely used is to check the book's citation history. The book's citation history will tell you if the book is cited by other works in the field, and how often. You can search Google Scholar for the book, to see how often the book is cited, and by whom. A lot of citations, and by well-known researchers, means that the book is widely used and well-accepted. A few citations, or citations by people outside the field, means that the book isn't widely used.

There is no perfect way to determine if a book is widely used or not. The best you can do is check for reviews, see if the book is referenced by other works in the field, and check the book's citation history.

instruction: How should I do time manage spreading time working on multiple projects? For example, should I "time block" your calendar and say 8am to 10am I work Project A. And 10am to 11am I work on Project B. What are other methods besides time blocking?

instruction: What is the best explanation of Newton’s laws?
output_1:
Newton's laws of motion are three scientific laws that, together, laid the foundation for classical mechanics. They describe the relationship between a body and the forces acting upon it, and its motion as a result. The three laws are as follows:

* The first law:
An object in motion will remain in motion, and an object at rest will remain at rest, unless an external force acts upon it. This is the law of inertia.

* The second law:
The rate of change of momentum of a body is directly proportional to the force acting on the body, and takes place in the direction in which the force acts. The mathematical expression of this is F=ma, where m is the mass of the body and a is its acceleration.

* The third law:
For every action there is an equal and opposite reaction. If object A exerts a force on object B, then object B exerts an equal force on object A.
output_2:
Isaac Newton’s three laws of motion are as follows:

1) An object at rest remains at rest, and an object in motion remains in motion, unless acted upon by a force.

2) The acceleration of an object is directly proportional to the magnitude of the object’s net force, and inversely proportional to the object’s mass. (F = ma)

3) For every action there is an equal and opposite reaction.

instruction: I'm buying a car for the first time, any advice?
output_1:
Here are some things to consider:

* Decide on a budget
* Think about what you want the car to do
* Look for a reliable model
* Test drive the car
* Negotiate the price
* Get an inspection
* Consider warranty and insurance

## Decide on a budget

1. Consider your needs. Decide what you will use the car for and how often you will drive it. Will you drive long distances? Carry passengers? Haul cargo? Drive in the city? Think about how often you will drive and if you will drive on highways or city streets. This will help you determine what type of car will best suit your needs.
2. Research the cost of a new car. Check online resources, such as Kelley Blue Book, to get a good idea of what new cars cost. Use this information to determine a realistic budget for your new car.
3. Research the cost of a used car. Check online resources, such as Kelley Blue Book, to get a good idea of what used cars cost. This will help you determine a realistic budget for a used car.
4. Create a budget. Add up all of your expenses and subtract them from your income. This will give you an idea of what you can spend on a car. Consider other expenses, such as gas, insurance, and maintenance, when creating your budget.


## Think about what you want the car to do

1. Consider your lifestyle. Think about how you live your life and what you need from a car. For example, if you travel often, you may need a car with a lot of trunk space. If you have kids, you may need a car with a lot of seating.
2. Consider your driving habits. Think about how you drive and what you need from a car. For example, if you drive in the city, you may need a car that handles well in traffic. If you drive on highways, you may need a car that gets good gas mileage.
3. Consider your driving environment. Think about where you live and what you need from a car. For example, if you live in an area with snow and ice, you may need a car with all-wheel drive. If you live in an area with heavy rain, you may need a car with good brakes.
4. Consider your needs. Think about what you need from a car and how it will fit into your life.


## Look for a reliable model

1. Research the car's safety ratings. Look up the car's safety ratings on sites like the Insurance Institute for Highway Safety and the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration. The higher the safety rating, the safer the car is likely to be.
2. Research the car's reliability. Look up the car's reliability on sites like Consumer Reports and JD Power. The higher the rating, the more likely the car is to be reliable.
3. Consider the car's features. Think about what features are important to you. For example, if you drive long distances, you may want a car with good fuel efficiency. If you have kids, you may want a car with good crash test scores.
4. Consider the car's cost. Think about how much you can afford to spend on a car. This will help you narrow down your search.
5. Consider the car's resale value. Think about how much the car will be worth when you want to sell it. This will help you determine if the car is a good investment.
6. Consider the car's maintenance costs. Think about how much it will cost to maintain the car. This will help you determine if the car is a good value.

instruction: Are there parallels between the use of radio communication by nationalists in the 1930’s and the use of social media/Twitter by nationalists in the present day? Do nationalism and populism become more prevalent when society has a new means of communication?
output_1:
It is an interesting question and there is some evidence that communication technologies can facilitate the spread of nationalism and populism.

In the 1930's, radio was a new and powerful medium that allowed the spread of nationalist and populist messages. This was particularly evident in Germany where the Nazi party used radio to great effect to spread their ideology and gain support. 

In the present day, social media and other forms of digital communication are similarly powerful tools that can be used to spread nationalist and populist messages. For example, in the 2016 US presidential election, Donald Trump's campaign used social media platforms like Facebook and Twitter to target their messages and gain support. 

In both cases, the rise of new communication technologies facilitated the spread of nationalist and populist messages. These messages typically prey on the fears and insecurities of people and tap into existing divisions in society.

It is important to note that nationalism and populism are not inherently negative forces. They can be used to promote positive change and advance the interests of marginalised groups. However, they can also be used to spread hate and division. 

The key is to use these technologies responsibly and to promote tolerance and understanding.
output_2: Yes, there are strong parallels between the use of radio communication by nationalists in the 1930’s and the use of social media/Twitter by nationalists in the present day. In both cases, a new technology of communication was co-opted by nationalists and populists to spread their messages and rally supporters. Nationalism and populism often flourish during times of social and economic disruption, and new technologies of communication can be highly effective tools for promoting nationalist and populist ideas. Radio was a revolutionary new technology in the 1930’s, and it was widely adopted for political purposes by nationalists and populists who used it to spread their messages of distrust and resentment towards “outsiders” and to mobilize supporters. A similar dynamic is playing out today with the rise of social media and especially Twitter, which has become a powerful tool for nationalist and populist leaders around the world. These leaders use Twitter to spread their nationalist and populist messages, and to rally their supporters and attack political opponents. The parallels between the use of radio in the 1930’s and Twitter today are striking, and show how new technologies of communication can be highly effective tools for promoting nationalism and populism.
